 with Intel 3, destroyed their margins. This isn=E2=80=99t a surprise: the =
reason why it is hard to skip steps is not just because technology advances=
, but because you have to actually learn on the line how to implement new t=
echnology at scale, with sustainable yield. Go back to Intel=E2=80=99s 10nm=
 failure: the company could technically make a 10nm chip, they just couldn=
=E2=80=99t do so economically; there are now open questions about Intel 3, =
much less next year=E2=80=99s promised 18A.
* Intel is dramatically ramping up its Lunar Lake architecture as it is the=
 only design the company has that is competitive with the Qualcomm ARM arch=
itecture undergirding Microsoft=E2=80=99s CoPilot+ PC initiative; the probl=
em is that Lunar Lake=E2=80=99s tiles =E2=80=94 including its CPU =E2=80=94=
 are made by TSMC, which is both embarrassing and also terrible for margins=
.
* The third problem is that the goal Gelsinger has been pushing for is the =
aforementioned 18A, yet Intel has yet to announce a truly committed at-scal=
e partner. Yes, the company is in talks with lots of folks and claims some =
number of secret agreements, but at this point the foundry strategy needs r=
eal proof points; unfortunately Intel itself ramping up on TSMC, even as it=
